45:59.933 --> 46:01.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their money back.

46:01.500 --> 46:04.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They raised 25000 percent
of what they actually need.

46:04.100 --> 46:09.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They create this -- what they
think is going to be a flop,
"Springtime For Hitler," and,

46:10.666 --> 46:15.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of course, it becomes a
hit, and they go to jail.

46:17.933 --> 46:20.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
These investors trusted
Bialystock and Bloom.

46:20.433 --> 46:22.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They couldn't
actually monitor them.

46:22.000 --> 46:23.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They turned out to be bad eggs.

46:23.800 --> 46:25.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That is the problem
with capital markets.

46:25.833 --> 46:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the problem with me
giving money to people and not
knowing what they end up doing.

46:29.033 --> 46:34.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But, of course,
for every Bialystock,
there's a Buffett, for
every Bernie Madoff,

46:36.033 --> 46:40.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
1,000 honest brokers,
because there have always
been two faces of finance.

46:41.566 --> 46:43.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIHIR DESAI: This is actually
my favorite book about finance.

46:43.900 --> 46:45.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's from 1688.

46:45.133 --> 46:47.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Yes, a
good year for finance.

46:47.300 --> 46:51.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIHIR DESAI: And it was
"Confusion de Confusiones."

46:51.200 --> 46:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He basically describes finance
as the most noble profession,
as well as the most notorious

46:58.133 --> 47:00.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
profession.

47:00.166 --> 47:02.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think we have lost sense
of the nobility part that he
describes, and we tend to focus

47:02.933 --> 47:05.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on the negative.

47:05.066 --> 47:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Desai, wanting
to accentuate the positive,
uses an exemplar of finance

47:10.333 --> 47:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from Willa Cather's 19th
century novel, "O Pioneers!"

47:12.966 --> 47:17.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIHIR DESAI: Alexandra
Bergson is this wonderful
character who is a farmer,
who starts by basically

47:19.400 --> 47:21.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doing a leveraged buyout of
farms near where she lives.

47:21.500 --> 47:23.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: She borrows
money in order to buy.

47:23.166 --> 47:25.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MIHIR DESAI: She borrows
a bunch of money to
buy all of these farms.

47:25.266 --> 47:27.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ACTRESS: Now, I
have figured it out.

47:27.233 --> 47:29.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We sell most of the cattle e
and the corn we have left over.

47:29.866 --> 47:31.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We buy the Lindstrom place.

47:31.933 --> 47:36.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Then we take out two loans
on our half-section and
buy Peter Crow's place.

47:36.033 --> 47:40.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIHIR DESAI: She ends up
engaging in transactions
that would be in any
finance textbook.

47:40.766 --> 47:43.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But she never loses
sight of who she is.

47:43.100 --> 47:47.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She never behaves in ways that
would suggest that she thinks
everything is due to her skill,

47:47.300 --> 47:48.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as opposed to luck.

47:48.833 --> 47:51.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's very conscious of and
very humble of her outcome.

47:51.400 --> 47:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTOR: You have worked wonders
with this land, Alexandra.

47:54.233 --> 47:57.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ACTRESS: Oh, we hadn't any of
us much to do with it, Carl.

47:57.300 --> 47:59.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
The land did it.

47:59.333 --> 48:03.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIHIR DESAI: We really need good
stories about finance, because
good stories will guide good

48:03.733 --> 48:05.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
behavior.

48:05.200 --> 48:07.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: It's a lesson Desai
tries to teach his students.

48:07.566 --> 48:11.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIHIR DESAI: Pick your stories
carefully, because you will
live your life by these stories.

48:11.733 --> 48:13.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Some of you might
pick Gordon Gekko.

48:13.466 --> 48:15.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't recommend it.

48:15.266 --> 48:17.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Alexandra Bergson is
a fantastic model.

48:17.366 --> 48:21.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: For the
"PBS NewsHour," this is
economics correspondent
Paul Solman reporting

48:21.233 --> 48:23.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from Boston.

48:23.366 --> 48:27.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Who knew
by watching all these
films that you could get
great economic advice?

48:29.300 --> 48:32.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, while writing his book,
Professor Desai says he was
surprised to discover how many

48:33.966 --> 48:37.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
great writers, painters
and musicians also
held jobs in finance.

48:39.833 --> 48:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can test your own knowledge
of these entrepreneurial
artists with our online
quiz at PBS.org/NewsHour.

48:43.266 --> 48:47.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Now to

48:54.333 --> 48:59.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
another in our Brief
But Spectacular series,
where we ask people to
describe their passions.

49:01.300 --> 49:04.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from
British activist and
attorney Alexander McLean.

49:04.233 --> 49:09.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He is the founder of the
Ugandan-based African
Prisons Project, which
seeks to improve the

49:10.333 --> 49:12.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
lives of people
imprisoned in Africa.

49:12.333 --> 49:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALEXANDER MCLEAN, Founder,
African Prisons Project: I
think that, with any of us, if

49:14.433 --> 49:18.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the world knew the thing about
us we are most ashamed of,
and that's all that they knew,

49:18.300 --> 49:22.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that's all that they were
interested in, society would
lose out, because each of us

49:22.600 --> 49:27.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has much more to offer than
the worst thing we have done.

49:31.400 --> 49:36.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have been working in prisons
in Uganda since I was 18,
spending a lot of time on death

49:38.233 --> 49:40.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
row, growing up with many
of the death row inmates.

49:40.833 --> 49:43.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They have become
like family to me.

49:43.366 --> 49:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have spent time in about 130
prisons all over the world.

49:47.700 --> 49:52.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have seen that they're filled
with people who are poor and
not educated, and not connected.

49:54.566 --> 49:58.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I was 19, I first
visited the women's prison
in Kampala, Uganda's capital.

50:00.000 --> 50:03.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's where many women
were on death row.

50:03.133 --> 50:06.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Often, they were there
for killing a husband.

50:06.100 --> 50:09.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Uganda has some of the highest
rates of domestic violence in
the world, and, sometimes, when

50:09.533 --> 50:14.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a woman fights back, she will
find herself on death row.

50:14.133 --> 50:17.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That time I met Susan, she
was sentenced to death for
killing her husband when she was

50:17.500 --> 50:19.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
21.

50:19.166 --> 50:22.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She shared her cell
designed for one person
with three other women.

50:22.233 --> 50:24.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She started a
school on death row.

50:24.066 --> 50:25.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She established a choir.

50:25.333 --> 50:27.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She was a lead in
the prison church.

50:27.333 --> 50:32.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I saw that Susan was
transforming her community
from the inside out.

50:32.066 --> 50:36.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The African Prisons Project got
her admitted into the University
of London in 2011 to study

50:36.533 --> 50:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for a law degree by
correspondence, as Nelson
Mandela had done from
prison in South Africa.

50:41.066 --> 50:45.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So,Susan was one of the
University of London's best
students in human rights law.

50:45.100 --> 50:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She established a legal aid
clinic in her prison, helping
scores of her fellow inmates

50:49.700 --> 50:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to be released from prison.

50:51.733 --> 50:55.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She led a case, Susan Kigula
and 417 others, where all of
the death row inmates in Uganda

50:57.900 --> 51:00.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
challenged the mandatory
death sentence for
murder and armed robbery.

51:00.966 --> 51:05.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As a result of this case,
Susan and hundreds of others
were released from death row.

51:07.100 --> 51:09.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's now completed
her law degree.

51:09.300 --> 51:12.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Uganda's most senior
judge invited her to apply
to join the judiciary.

51:12.233 --> 51:17.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She said: I won't, and now I'm
going to train women in prison
in the law, so they can use

51:18.566 --> 51:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the law to protect their
families and their communities.

51:20.533 --> 51:25.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're in the process of
establishing the world's first
prison-based law college.

51:27.400 --> 51:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're then going to establish a
prison-based law firm, through
which they provide services

51:29.700 --> 51:31.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to their peers.

51:31.700 --> 51:34.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have seen about 3,000 people
released from prison in Uganda
and Kenya, having accessed

51:34.800 --> 51:38.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
legal services from
prisoners and prison
staff we have trained.

51:38.000 --> 51:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The law is seen as
a profession for the
privileged, for the elite.

51:42.400 --> 51:44.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We want to change that thinking.

51:44.300 --> 51:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We recognize that, actually, the
law is here to serve all of us.

51:48.100 --> 51:53.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We want to see people getting
out of prison, becoming lawyers
and judges, and politicians,

51:55.066 --> 51:58.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and legal academics, and
business leaders, going from the
margins of society to the center

51:58.733 --> 52:00.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of it.

52:00.666 --> 52:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
My name is Alexander McLean.

52:02.700 --> 52:07.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is my Brief But Spectacular
take on the power of the law
in the hands of the poor.

52:10.133 --> 52:13.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
