52:23.400 --> 52:27.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Navy teams around the globe
are often called in to
assist in rescue efforts.

52:27.033 --> 52:32.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But, this week, one
maritime mission in the
Indian Ocean helped a
unique creature in need.

52:33.700 --> 52:36.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The "NewsHour"'s Julia
Griffin explains.

52:36.033 --> 52:41.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIA GRIFFIN: It was a routine
patrol for a Sri Lankan naval
team Tuesday morning, when

52:43.033 --> 52:46.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they spotted something unusual
bobbing among the ocean waves,
not a bird or a boat, but

52:48.200 --> 52:52.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
rather a fully grown Asian
elephant, struggling to stay
afloat nearly 10 miles offshore.

52:54.900 --> 52:59.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Elephants are some of the
best swimmers of land mammals,
thanks to buoyant bodies and

53:01.166 --> 53:04.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
trunks that can be
used as snorkels, but
this pachyderm appeared
fatigued and distressed.

53:06.233 --> 53:09.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Officials believe the
animal had been trying
to cross the Kokkilai
Lagoon off the country's

53:09.666 --> 53:13.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
northeast coast when it
was swept out to sea.

53:13.700 --> 53:18.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Deciding to intervene, the
Navy and Department of Wildlife
dispatched additional teams to

53:18.233 --> 53:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the area, initiating a
mammoth-sized rescue effort.

53:21.966 --> 53:26.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The divers plunged
into the salty water to
soothe the elephant and
loop a tow rope around

53:27.633 --> 53:29.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
its body.

53:29.700 --> 53:34.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Over the next 12 hours, they
gently towed Jumbo, as it was
affectionately dubbed, back

53:34.266 --> 53:36.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the Sri Lankan coast.

53:36.800 --> 53:41.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as day turned to
night, rescue teams
reached their destination,
releasing Jumbo exhausted

53:42.900 --> 53:45.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but alive into
the shallow water.

53:45.100 --> 53:47.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
For the "PBS NewsHour,"
I'm Julia Griffin.

53:47.866 --> 53:50.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What
a happy ending.

53:50.533 --> 53:53.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And who knew that
elephants could swim?

